post_text:
Dear Parents,

We are so glad to be back! We are excited about being able to offer a virtual education path for our students. If your child has enrolled in virtual education, please be sure to stop by the school library and pick up your computer and information packet.

We would like for this transition to be as smooth as possible for our students. However, it is a new process for us and like all new processes, has a few kinks to work out. Thank you for being patient during this time. We are committed to providing the best educational experience possible for all of our students.

This Friday, August 28th will be a virtual day for all students. Students should have instructions from their teachers for classwork on this day. You can also visit the website for more information or email your teacher. If you are having trouble connecting with your teacher, please call the school with contact information and we will get right back to you. Thank you!

Bart Watkins
Superintendent

Dear Parents,
After much consideration we have decided to delay the start of the school year. Classes will now begin on Monday, August 24th. Meet the teacher will be by appointment. You may call the school at (405) 969-2227 Monday -Thursday from 9-3 to schedule a time to drop off supplies and see your child‚Äôs classroom before the 24th. We are very excited to see everyone. We know that this will be a great year, because we have great students, parents and teachers. We appreciate your willingness to work with us in handling new and challenging situations.

COVID-19 cases are high in Logan County, and that has affected this decision, but starting later will also allow us to receive and prepare‚Ä¶

post_text:
Dear Parents,
It has been confirmed that there are COVID-19 positive test results in our student population. In an effort to be exceedingly cautious with the safety of our students, the School Board met this evening and has voted to change the school calendar. The first day of school will be delayed until August 18th. Meet the Teacher will be Monday, August 17th. To make up the time in the days that were originally scheduled before August 18th, the school day has been extended for 10 minutes and will now release at 3:30 pm. Please see the school website at www.crescentok.com for a complete updated school calendar and further information. We at Crescent Schools hold our students‚Äô safety as our first priority and will make every effort to ensure that their school experience is safe.

Bart Watkins
Crescent Public School Superintendent

Dear Crescent Students and Parents,

I am sure you are aware that the State Department of Education has voted to move all instruction to an online platform for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. All extra-curricular activities are cancelled. We are extremely saddened that we will not be able to gather with our students during this time, but we understand the need for safety and precaution. We are waiting for the end of the quarantine to discuss rescheduling of milestone events like graduation. We want to provide every resource we can to you as parents to support our families at this time.

Virtual instruction will begin on April 6 and end on May 14. We will continue to have school‚Ä¶

Exciting news! üéâ We have partnered with OETA to provide in-home learning opportunities for students. The goal is to bring parents, students and teachers together with content and curriculum to meet educational needs while schools are closed due to coronavirus.

Beginning Monday, March 30, OETA will be adjusting its daytime schedule to provide curriculum-based programming for students over the air on its broadcast channel, OETA WORLD. Programs will include PBS favorites like NOVA, Nature, American Experience and PBS KIDS programming.

Programming changes to OETA WORLD will take place Monday through Friday from 6 a.m. until 6 p.m. until the end of the school year.

Teachers and parents are encouraged to visit OETA.tv/LearningAtHome to view an updated program schedule, OETA‚Äôs statewide channel list, curriculum and activities.

Toward that end, we will begin providing lunches on Monday, March 23rd through April 6th (on Monday -Thursday) through a Child Nutrition Grant. Lunches will be provided at no cost to students or the school. If you would like to receive a lunch for your students, please email lleniger@crescentok.com with an address, names of students, and any food allergies. All children ages 1-18 qualify, whether they are registered students at CPS or not. Lunches for rural students will be delivered. Lunches for the Twin Lakes area will be dropped off at the office. Lunches for Lake Lottawanna will be dropped off by Ms. Stacy‚Äôs house. Lunches for students located in Crescent can be picked up at the cafeteria. Please let us know as quickly as possible so that we can formulate a plan for delivery. We are so glad we are able to provide this service for our children. If you have questions you can call the school Monday, March 23rd between 8 and 10 am. (405) 969-3738 or (405) 969-2545 Thank you!!

post_text:
Teacher Spotlight:
Get to know your Crescent Public School Teachers:

Mrs. Tammy Payne has been an educator for 20 years. During that time she has taught 1st, 2nd, 4th, 5th and 6th grades, as well as music. She has also spent a few years as an assistant principal and a reading coach, but her heart is in the classroom, where she currently teaches 5th and 6th grade math. She loves to see kids "get it" when they are working on math problems.
Tammy is married to John Payne and they have five children. Jerod and his wife Shelby, Zach, Mason, Sadie and Addison. She has one amazing grandbaby, Maddox. Her favorite places to be are in the mountains, at the lake, by the fire, at church, shopping in Stillwater (Go Pokes!) or anywhere she can hang out with family and friends and soak up some quality time with them. Her favorite drink is coffee with sugar-free french vanilla creamer, and she is a fan of dark chocolate as well. You are doing an awesome job Mrs. Payne and we are so glad you're here!

post_text:
Teacher Spotlight!
Get to know your Crescent Public School Teachers!!

Meet Mr. Stephen Parker--this is his 40th year of teaching, his 6th at Crescent. Mr. Parker teaches Fundamentals of Technology, Multi-Media, Desktop Publishing, and Accounting. He has 3 Children, a Son in Little Rock, a Daughter in Denver, and a Daughter in Dallas. He has 2 grandsons and one on the way in April! Parker's favorite foods are Crow Creek Burgers and Reeses. He loves sports and coached football in Oklahoma and Texas for 30 years. His favorite teaching moments have happened when his graduates have found him and shared their stock investment successes that were learned in their financial literacy sections. He is inspired by his mother, who is 86 years old and still travels to Las Vegas to get her 3 free nights at the Palazzo. He says she, and the Crescent Students, keep him young. We are glad you're here!!

Teacher Spotlight:
Get to know your Crescent Public School Teachers!

Karl Butt, better known as Coach B, is in his ninth year of teaching elementary PE, coaching girls' fast pitch and slow pitch softball and girls' basketball at Crescent Public School. His favorite food is a burrito with green chiles. When he is not running off those burritos, or completing obstacle course races, he likes to watch MASH and Jeopardy. But let's be honest, our coaches spend most of their time at the gym. Coach B's favorite part of being a teacher is getting to joke with the kids every day. He is inspired by ultra-marathon runner David Goggins. We are
delighted to have Coach B on staff at Crescent!

It's hard to believe the path I've been led down! Today, I will be cheering on Crescent High School's first EVER Esports team at their first EVER HS Super Smash Bro's Ultimate tournament!

The tournament is at OCU Wanda L. Bass School of Music, 2501 N Blackwelder Ave, Oklahoma City, OK 73106.

This will be an all day event and the fun begins at 9:00am! You are welcome to come witness history in the making! Proud to be their Coach/Sponsor!

A Special Thanks to Level Up Arcade for helping with the cost of our Team Shirts! We are so thankful for their sponsorship!!

post_text:
We are so excited for our new facility!!

We will be rearranging the school schedule to accommodate the beginning of the FEMA building. The crane is scheduled to arrive on Wednesday the 25th of this month. The crane is 230 feet tall, which requires a safety zone (no students or staff) of more than 230 feet. Due to safety concerns, there will be no after school program on the 25th and NO SCHOOL ON SEPTEMBER 26th. We will go to school on Friday, October 4th to make up the day of school.

On the 25th, as soon as school is out Coreslab will begin erecting the building. The wall panels are roughly 20 feet tall and 10 feet wide. The roof pieces are 100 feet long and weigh around 80,000 pounds. If the weather cooperates, the FEMA structure will be standing by the end of Saturday. There is a small chance that the start of the next week could be impacted.
Thank you for your patience!!

Bart Watkins
Superintendent/HS Principal
Crescent Public Schools
bwatkins@crescentok.com
405-969-3738 ext. 1010
106 N. Magnolia
Crescent, Ok. 73028
